Below are the pictures of @GMapsPlatform satellite view.Desktop view on left and mobile app view on right. Desktop shows ~10year old data, but mobile app shows latest.@Google is this a bug? or don't want to update desktop api? #io19extended @sundarpichai #gmaps #satellitepic.twitter.com/2RUIlaG8LN

It may not be an issue, depending on how long it takes for that to kick in. Perhaps can be alleviated if it is relational to distance from an action. Longer distance->user action, dimming of UX. Shorter distance->user action, AR overlay allowed.

This is the complicated part. User safety v usability. The problem is that if the user is using this as an accessibility feature (which it really can and ought to be), blocking the user from using the feature in motion *may* inhibit accessibility for the disabled. @googlemaps /1 pic.twitter.com/cpKVAauX3L

Ahh back to that time of year when I have to e mail all customers and tell them not to use @googlemaps. All the other apps will take them to the right place. Google - wrong road, wrong building, wrong photo. Apart from that it's not too bad.
I have completed this process multiple times with no luck, which is why my last resort was to tweet about my issue in hopes of receiving help.

The last time that happened to my phone I had to replace the motherboard days later (flash memory died). This tweet brings me horrible flashbacks (unintended pun there).

Here's hoping your case is not even remotely close to being that bad and just a case of Artem's Luck

If you drive carefully and shift down (to 3rd, second, etc.) in the appropriate spots (rather than riding your brakes) -- and don't speed like crazy downhill while texting and Snapchatting!! -- not too bad.
